# Khaao backend — environment variables (v3)
#
# Quick start: `cp .env.example .env`, fill in the blanks below, then
# `go run ./cmd/server`. Everything here is read once at boot (see
# internal/config/config.go) — restart the server after any edit.
#
# This file is a TEMPLATE (tracked in git) — never put real keys in it.
# Real values go in `.env` (gitignored, see the repo root .gitignore).
#
# ============================================================================
# HOW TO GET EACH KEY — step by step
# ============================================================================
#
# 1) FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID (required unless AUTH_FAKE=true)
#    - Go to https://console.firebase.google.com
#    - "Add project" (or open an existing one) → give it any name, e.g. "khaao".
#      You can decline Google Analytics, it isn't needed.
#    - Once created: ⚙️ (gear icon, top-left) → "Project settings" → General tab
#      → the very first field is "Project ID". Copy that exact string here.
#    - Still on that project: Build → Authentication → "Get started" →
#      Sign-in method tab → enable "Google" as a sign-in provider. Without
#      this step, Google sign-in will fail even with a correct project ID.
#    - Before going live: Authentication → Settings → "Authorized domains" →
#      add your production domain. This is the #1 launch gotcha — sign-in
#      silently fails on unlisted domains. (This "Authorized domains" list is
#      about which WEBSITE origins may host the sign-in popup — e.g. localhost
#      and your production domain. It is unrelated to ALLOWED_EMAIL_DOMAIN
#      below, which is about which STUDENT EMAIL addresses may register. You
#      need both.)
#
#    Q: We only use Firebase for auth — why does the BACKEND need a Firebase
#       env var too, isn't that a frontend-only thing?
#    A: No — the frontend and backend need Firebase for two different jobs,
#       and both are required:
#         - Frontend: needs the full SDK config (api key, app id, etc. below)
#           to show the Google sign-in popup and get the user an ID token.
#         - Backend: takes that ID token and must verify it's genuine — not
#           forged, not expired, and (critically) not a token issued for
#           someone else's Firebase project. That check (internal/authn/
#           firebase.go) validates the token's signature against Google's
#           public certs AND checks the token's "audience"/"issuer" claims
#           match FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID. Without it, the backend would accept
#           a valid-looking Google ID token from ANY Firebase project, not
#           just yours — a real security hole.
#       The backend only needs this one Project ID string, not the rest of
#       the frontend's config (no api key, no service-account file needed).
#
# 2) DATABASE_URL (Postgres connection string)
#    - Local dev (Homebrew Postgres on macOS), one-time setup:
#        brew install postgresql@15 && brew services start postgresql@15
#        createdb khaao
#      Then use: postgres://<your-mac-username>@localhost:5432/khaao?sslmode=disable
#      (find your username by running `whoami`; no password needed locally).
#    - Hosted Postgres for staging/production (any of these work — pick one,
#      create a database, and each will show you a ready-made connection
#      string to paste here):
#        Supabase   → supabase.com → New project → Project Settings →
#                     Database → "Connection string" (URI tab)
#        Neon       → neon.tech → New project → Dashboard shows the
#                     connection string immediately
#        Railway    → railway.app → New Project → Add PostgreSQL →
#                     Variables tab → DATABASE_URL
#    - Whichever you use, the URL must end with a real database name and
#      usually `?sslmode=require` for hosted providers (not `disable`).
#
# 3) JWT_SECRET (signs Khaao's own session tokens, unrelated to Firebase)
#    - Generate one locally, don't type it by hand:
#        openssl rand -base64 48
#    - Paste the output here. Must be at least 32 characters in production
#      (enforced by config.Validate — the server refuses to boot otherwise).
#    - Rotating this value logs every signed-in user out immediately.
#
# 4) SHOPKEEPER_EMAILS (who is allowed to sign in as the canteen staff)
#    - Just the real Google account email(s) of the shopkeeper(s), comma
#      separated, e.g.: canteen.owner@gmail.com,manager@sst.scaler.com
#    - These do NOT need to be on the ALLOWED_EMAIL_DOMAIN — that's the point
#      of this list, it's the allowlist exception for staff. Seeded into the
#      shopkeeper_emails DB table on every boot (existing rows are untouched;
#      you can also add more shopkeepers later directly in that table).
#
# 5) ALLOWED_EMAIL_DOMAIN — the students' Google Workspace domain (e.g. your
#    college's @college.edu). Not a secret, just needs to match reality.
#    This is enforced server-side in internal/services/auth.go on every
#    login — it is separate from (and in addition to) Firebase's own
#    "Authorized domains" list mentioned in #1 above.
#
# No other variable below needs an external account — they're all plain
# config values with sensible defaults for local dev.
# ============================================================================

# HTTP port the server listens on.
PORT=8080

# dev | test | production. production runs fail-closed validation (see
# config.Validate) and refuses to boot with any dev-default value below.
APP_ENV=dev

# Postgres connection string (Postgres is the only supported DB in v3).
# See "HOW TO GET EACH KEY" #2 above.
DATABASE_URL=postgres://lingaraghavendra@localhost:5432/khaao?sslmode=disable

# Secret used to sign Khaao session JWTs. See #3 above. Change this in any
# real deployment — the placeholder below is rejected in production.
JWT_SECRET=dev-secret-change-me

# --- Firebase auth (the ONLY login method) -----------------------------------

# See "HOW TO GET EACH KEY" #1 above.
FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=

# Students must sign in with a Google account on this domain.
ALLOWED_EMAIL_DOMAIN=sst.scaler.com

# See "HOW TO GET EACH KEY" #4 above.
SHOPKEEPER_EMAILS=

# DEV ONLY. true = accept fake tokens ("fake:<email>") so e2e tests can run
# without Google/Firebase set up at all. NEVER enable in production — the
# server actively refuses to boot with AUTH_FAKE=true when APP_ENV=production.
AUTH_FAKE=false

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Minutes a fully-ready order holds before it expires and returns its units
# to the pool (orders with anything already handed over never expire).
HOLD_MINUTES=15

# IANA timezone for business-day/date logic (daily token reset, history dates,
# menu availability windows). Keep this as the canteen's local zone regardless
# of where the server itself runs.
BUSINESS_TIMEZONE=Asia/Kolkata

# Origin allowed by CORS — the frontend's URL. Must be an exact scheme+host
# match (e.g. https://khaao.example.com), and must be https:// in production.
FRONTEND_ORIGIN=http://localhost:5173

# Seed ~6 sample Indian canteen menu items on boot if the menu table is empty.
# Handy for a first run; set to false once you've added your real menu.
SEED_SAMPLE_MENU=true
